<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1600,2022]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
The above definition more clearly defines and distinguishes the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[985,1086,1600,1626]" class="Insecta" genus="Iteaphila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[985,1086,1600,1626]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Iteaphila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and excludes the species of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sinclair &amp; Shamshev" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Bezzi" baseAuthorityYear="1924" box="[151,329,1636,1662]" class="Insecta" genus="Iteaphila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="setosa">
<emphasis box="[151,329,1636,1662]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Iteaphila setosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group (
<figureCitation box="[504,577,1636,1662]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1385,1409]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,345,1359]" captionTargetId="figure-103@8.[151,1435,345,1361]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Photographs of living species of Paraiteaphila and Iteaphila with unbranched R 4+5. 1, Iteaphila sp., female, lateral view, Hoh River, Washington, USA (photograph @ S. Marshall); 2, I. bifida sp. nov., lateral view, male on Shepherdia flowers, British Columbia, Canada (photograph @ A. Borkent); 3, Iteaphila sp., oblique dorsal view, Mt. Washington, New Hampshire, USA (photograph @ T. Murray); 4, Paraiteaphila italica (Loew), near Pizzo Camarda (AQ), Italy, 42°27′22.2″N 13°27′07.7″E (photograph @ E. Santarelli)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4745570" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4745570/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Figs 4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[589,620,1636,1662]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–10" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1171,1195]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1147]" captionTargetId="figure-19@10.[151,1435,181,1147]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 8–10. Species of Paraiteaphila and Iteaphila with unbranched R 4+5, lateral view. 8, I. longipalpis, male, scale bar = 1 mm; 9, I. parastentor, male, scale bar = 0.5 mm; 10, Paraiteaphila sp., female, scale bar = 0.75 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4745574" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4745574/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">10</figureCitation>
). These species are here transferred to a new genus diagnosed below.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1600,2022]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<taxonomicName box="[199,300,1672,1698]" class="Insecta" genus="Iteaphila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[199,300,1672,1698]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Iteaphila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is exclusively a Holarctic genus and the Chilean species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Collin, 1933" authorityName="Collin" authorityYear="1933" box="[959,1366,1672,1698]" class="Insecta" genus="Anthepiscopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="extimus">
<emphasis box="[959,1217,1672,1698]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Anthepiscopus extimus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Collin, J. E." box="[1224,1366,1672,1698]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="1 - 334" refId="ref83823" refString="Collin, J. E. (1933) Empididae. Diptera of Patagonia and South Chile, 4, 1 - 334." type="journal article" year="1933">Collin, 1933</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is not congeneric. This species is conspecific with “new genus 2”, originally thought to be related to 
<taxonomicName box="[1238,1339,1708,1734]" class="Insecta" genus="Iteaphila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1238,1339,1708,1734]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Iteaphila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because of the angle of the proboscis and flower visiting habits (
<bibRefCitation author="Sinclair, B. J. &amp; Cumming, J. M." box="[802,1111,1744,1770]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="161 - 186" refId="ref85207" refString="Sinclair, B. J. &amp; Cumming, J. M. (2000) Revision of the genus Apterodromia (Diptera: Empidoidea), with a redefinition of the tribe Ocydromiini. Records of the Australian Museum, 52, 161 - 186. https: // doi. org / 10.3853 / j. 0067 - 1975.52.2000.1313" type="journal article" year="2000">Sinclair &amp; Cumming 2000</bibRefCitation>
) and is presently tentatively assigned to the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Melander" baseAuthorityYear="1965" box="[327,448,1780,1806]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Empidinae">Empidinae</taxonomicName>
(Rafael 
<emphasis box="[547,597,1780,1806]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">et al</emphasis>
., in prep.). This undescribed genus is characterized also by both branched and unbranched R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[356,382,1834,1848]" fontSize="6" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">4+5</subScript>
species, complete precoxal bridge, arched palpi, epipharyngeal blades present, slender stylus, row of long, erect setae at base of prementum, upright epandrium without dorsal bridge, long slender phallus, hypoproct not produced into processes and postgonites present.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1600,2022]" lastBlockId="9.[151,1436,151,357]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="10" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,458,1923,1949]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Genitalic homologies.</emphasis>
The revision of this group of species enabled us to confirm the genitalic homologies of the processes arising from near the base of the phallus, associated lateral apodemes (especially enlarged in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sinclair &amp; Shamshev" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Melander" box="[151,215,1996,2021]" class="Insecta" genus="Iteaphila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nupta">
<emphasis box="[151,215,1996,2021]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">nupta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group) and paired flanking processes. The confusion was created by the posterior displacement of where the phallus and hypandrium come together. The phallus articulates with a narrow bridge from which the paired, closely approximated median postgonites arch dorsally (
<figureCitation box="[797,886,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 36–40" captionStartId="31.[151,264,1842,1866]" captionTargetBox="[168,1426,337,1780]" captionTargetId="figure-79@31.[151,1436,309,1819]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURES 36–40. Male terminalia of Iteaphila with unbranched R 4+5, lateral view. 36, I. longiphallus sp. nov.; 37, I. arnaudi sp. nov.; 38, I. bayarea sp. nov.; 39, same, apex of hypandrium, posterior view; 40, Iteaphila sp., apex of hypandrium, posterior view. Scale bar = 0.1 mm. Abbreviations: pgt—postgonite; ph—phallus; ph gd—phallic guide; sur—surstylus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4745596" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4745596/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Figs 37</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[900,932,186,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 58–61" captionStartId="59.[151,264,1870,1894]" captionTargetBox="[176,1429,299,1808]" captionTargetId="figure-59@59.[151,1436,273,1847]" captionTargetPageId="59" captionText="FIGURES 58–61. Male terminalia of Iteaphila with unbranched R, lateral view. 58, I. subnupta sp. nov.; 59, I. aktruensis 4+5 sp. nov.; 60, I. incus sp. nov.; 61, I. miranda sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.1 mm. Abbreviations: pgt—postgonite; ph—phallus; sur—surstylus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4745610" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4745610/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">58</figureCitation>
). Also associated with the bridge are paired inner apodemes between the ejaculatory and gonocoxal apodemes (
<figureCitation box="[911,994,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURES 29–32" captionStartId="24.[151,264,1697,1721]" captionTargetBox="[164,1432,193,1652]" captionTargetId="figure-19@24.[151,1436,181,1674]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 29–32. Male terminalia of Iteaphila with unbranched R 4+5, lateral view. 29, I. bartaki sp. nov.; 30, I. falki sp. nov.; 31, I. kyrgyzstanensis sp. nov.; 32, I. ribesii (Becker). Scale bar = 0.1 mm. Abbreviations: cerc—cercus; ej apod—ejaculatory apodeme; goncx apod—gonocoxal apodeme; hypd—hypandrium; hyprct proc—hypoproct process; i apod—inner apodeme; ph—phallus; ph gd—phallic guide; sur—surstylus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4745590" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4745590/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
, i apod). The paired processes flanking the phallus are termed the phallic guide (
<figureCitation box="[606,693,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 29–32" captionStartId="24.[151,264,1697,1721]" captionTargetBox="[164,1432,193,1652]" captionTargetId="figure-19@24.[151,1436,181,1674]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 29–32. Male terminalia of Iteaphila with unbranched R 4+5, lateral view. 29, I. bartaki sp. nov.; 30, I. falki sp. nov.; 31, I. kyrgyzstanensis sp. nov.; 32, I. ribesii (Becker). Scale bar = 0.1 mm. Abbreviations: cerc—cercus; ej apod—ejaculatory apodeme; goncx apod—gonocoxal apodeme; hypd—hypandrium; hyprct proc—hypoproct process; i apod—inner apodeme; ph—phallus; ph gd—phallic guide; sur—surstylus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4745590" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4745590/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Figs 32</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[705,734,258,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 53–57" captionStartId="52.[151,264,1898,1922]" captionTargetBox="[160,1424,322,1839]" captionTargetId="figure-63@52.[151,1436,309,1875]" captionTargetPageId="52" captionText="FIGURES 53–57. Male terminalia of Iteaphila with unbranched R 4+5. 53, I. luteitibia sp. nov., lateral view; 54, I. nupta (Melander), lateral view; 55, I. sierrensis sp. nov., lateral view; 56, I. spinosa sp. nov., lateral view; 57, same, left cercus, dorsal view. Scale bar = 0.1 mm. Abbreviations: cerc—cercus; hypd—hypandrium; hyprct proc—hypoproct process; ph—phallus; ph gd—phallic guide; sur—surstylus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4745608" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4745608/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">53</figureCitation>
) and appear to be associated with an apical invagination of the hypandrium which arches anteriorly beneath the phallus and guide as far as the base of the phallic guide, but this region is mostly membranous and it is difficult to follow connections.
</paragraph>
